{{en-verb}}

# {{senseid|en|seduce, entrance or fascinate}}To [[seduce]], [[persuade]] or [[fascinate]] someone or something.
#* {{w|John Milton}}
#*: They, on their mirth and dance / Intent, with jocund music '''charm''' his ear.
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=4
|passage=The Celebrity, by arts unknown, induced Mrs. Judge Short and two other ladies to call at Mohair on an afternoon when Mr. Cooke was trying a trotter on the track. The three returned wondering and '''charmed''' with Mrs. Cooke; they were sure she had had no hand in the furnishing of that atrocious house.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|He '''charmed''' her with his dashing tales of his days as a sailor.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To use a [[magical]] charm upon; to subdue, control, or summon by incantation or supernatural influence.
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}}
#*: No witchcraft '''charm''' thee!
#: {{usex|lang=en|After winning three games while wearing the chain, Dan began to think it had been '''charmed'''.}}
# To protect with, or make invulnerable by, spells, charms, or supernatural influences.
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}}
#*: I, in my own woe '''charmed''', / Could not find death.
#: {{usex|lang=en|She led a '''charmed''' life.}}
# {{context|obsolete|rare|lang=en}} To make music upon.
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}}
#*: Here we our slender pipes may safely '''charm'''.
# To subdue or overcome by some secret power, or by that which gives pleasure; to allay; to soothe.
#* {{w|Alexander Pope}}
#*: Music the fiercest grief can '''charm'''.

